The [economy of Ethiopia](/Economy_of_Ethiopia) is, for those keeping score, a rather intricate tapestry woven from the threads of a [mixed](/Mixed_economy) and [transition economy](/Transition_economy). It’s an ongoing experiment, primarily characterized by a sizable public sector that the [government of Ethiopia](/Government_of_Ethiopia) is, with visible reluctance and perhaps a touch of bureaucratic fatigue, in the midst of [privatizing](/Privatization). The grand vision, if you care for such things, is a gradual pivot toward a more dynamic [market economy](/Market_economy) [26](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Sanchez-26).

One might observe, with a sigh, that key pillars of this evolving economic landscape—specifically the [banking](/Banking_in_Ethiopia), [telecommunication](/Telecommunications_in_Ethiopia), and [transportation](/Transport_in_Ethiopia) sectors—remain firmly under the thumb of [government-owned](/List_of_government-owned_companies_of_Ethiopia) entities [27](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Maasho_4G-27) [28](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Maasho_sells-28). It seems some things are just too strategic to relinquish, at least for the foreseeable future.

Despite its inherent complexities and the perpetual state of flux, [Ethiopia](/Ethiopia) has managed to carve out a reputation for possessing one of the fastest-growing economies on the global stage, a feat made all the more notable by its status as Africa's second most populous nation [29](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-IFC_Boosts-29). A significant portion of this growth narrative involves the methodical [privatization](/Privatization) of numerous properties that were once firmly in the state's grip under the previous [regime](/Regime). This process, along with the anticipated liberalization of its [financial](/Finance) sector, suggests a future where the private sector might finally stretch its legs [30](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Reuters_sells-30). However, as is often the case, there are caveats: sectors such as [telecommunications](/Communications_in_Ethiopia), [financial](/Finance) and insurance services, air and [land transportation](/Land_transport) services, and retail are conspicuously designated as "strategic." This means they are expected to remain firmly under state control, perhaps indefinitely, like treasured heirlooms too valuable to be sold off.

A demographic quirk, or perhaps a looming challenge, is that nearly half of Ethiopia's population is under the tender age of 18. While there has been a commendable surge in educational enrollment at both primary and tertiary levels, the rate of [job creation](/Job_creation) has, predictably, lagged behind the burgeoning number of graduates. The country faces the Sisyphean task of generating hundreds of thousands of jobs annually just to keep pace with its relentless [population growth](/Population_growth) [31](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Economist_brittle-31). A truly inspiring challenge, if you’re into that sort of thing.

In 2023, Ethiopia's [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) was an estimated $156.1 billion in [nominal](/GDP_(nominal)) terms and a rather more substantial $393.85 billion when adjusted for [Purchasing Power Parity (PPP)](/Purchasing_power_parity). This economic output is largely underpinned by a services-based economy, with a significant contribution from [agriculture](/Primary_sector_of_the_economy) [32](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-IMF.org-32). The nation's trade relationships are globally diverse; in 2019, its primary trading partners included [China](/China), the [United States](/United_States), the [UAE](/United_Arab_Emirates), [France](/France), the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), [South Korea](/South_Korea), [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia), [Germany](/Germany), [Japan](/Japan), [Switzerland](/Switzerland), the [Netherlands](/Netherlands), [Belgium](/Belgium), [Turkey](/Turkey), [India](/India), and [Egypt](/Egypt) [33](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-OEC_import-33). By 2021, the composition of the economy saw [agriculture](/Primary_sector_of_the_economy) contributing 37.5% of the total economic output, [services](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy) 36.25%, and [industry](/Secondary_sector_of_the_economy) 21.85% [34](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Statista_sectors-34). For those contemplating an entrepreneurial venture, Ethiopia's economy ranked 159th out of 190 countries in terms of 'Ease of doing business' – a statistic that speaks volumes, perhaps, about the inherent friction in its economic gears [35](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Statista_ease-35).

Ethiopia is also an active participant in regional and global economic blocs, including the [African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA)](/African_Continental_Free_Trade_Agreement), the [Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA)](/Common_Market_for_Eastern_and_Southern_Africa), the [Intergovernmental Authority on Development (IGAD)](/Intergovernmental_Authority_on_Development), and the [G24](/Group_of_24). It holds observer status at the [World Trade Organization (WTO)](/World_Trade_Organization), patiently waiting for its turn, presumably. In a more recent development, Ethiopia officially joined the [BRICS](/BRICS) economic alliance in January 2024, a move that undoubtedly added another layer to its already complex international economic identity [36](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-SCMP_BRICS-36).

While Ethiopia may not currently boast a bustling [stock exchange](/Stock_exchange), it's worth noting that one did exist during the reign of [Emperor Haile Selassie I](/Haile_Selassie), known rather poetically as an 'ākisīyoni gebeya.' Today, however, the primary organized market for commodities is the [Ethiopia Commodity Exchange](/Ethiopia_Commodity_Exchange) in [Addis Ababa](/Addis_Ababa), which has been facilitating trade since its establishment in 2008 [37](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-IFPRI_Commodity-37).

A less glamorous, but equally significant, aspect of the Ethiopian economy is its substantial [foreign debt](/External_debt), which currently stands at an overall external debt of $28 billion USD. A considerable slice of this, over $13 billion, is owed to [China](/China) [38](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Bloomberg_IMF-38). Despite this, its debt-to-GDP ratio is comparatively smaller than those of many similar and neighboring countries, a small comfort perhaps. The nation's [foreign reserves](/Foreign_exchange_reserves) are currently reported at $2.4 billion, a figure that has unfortunately seen a decline in recent years [38](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Bloomberg_IMF-38).

Ethiopia, with a blend of ambition and optimism, aims to achieve national [middle-income](/Middle_income_country) status by 2025 [39](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-UN_working_paper-39). Yet, the stark reality, as illuminated by 2019 data, reveals that 68.7% of the population is still grappling with [multidimensional poverty](/Multidimensional_Poverty_Index), with an additional 18.4% teetering on the edge of vulnerability [40](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-UNDP_MPI_2023-40). It seems even ambitious targets can't entirely erase the pervasive shadows of economic hardship.

