## History

Main article: [Economic history of Ethiopia](/Economic_history_of_Ethiopia)

### Development of GDP per capita

It’s almost quaint to consider that [Ethiopia's](/Ethiopia) geographical position and inherent resources have allowed it to maintain connections with the broader world for centuries, a privilege not universally shared among [sub-Saharan African](/Sub-Saharan_Africa) nations [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). From antiquity, Ethiopian traders were, in their own way, globalists, exchanging precious [gold](/Gold), exotic [ivory](/Ivory), elusive [musk](/Musk), and valuable wild animal skins for more mundane but essential commodities like salt, and, of course, luxury items such as silk and velvet [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). By the late nineteenth century, [coffee](/Coffee) had transcended its status as a mere beverage ingredient to become one of Ethiopia's most vital [cash crops](/Cash_crop) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Trade at this time predominantly followed two significant [trade routes](/Trade_route), both originating in the fertile Kefa-Jima region in the far southwest. One artery stretched northward, passing through [Gonder](/Gondar) and Adwa, culminating in Mitsiwa, while the other traced the path of the [Awash River](/Awash_River) valley to [Harer](/Harar), before reaching the Red Sea ports of [Berbera](/Berbera) or [Zeila](/Zeila) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

However, the grandeur of Ethiopia as a major trading power waned significantly after the decline of [Axum](/Axum). A curious cultural shift occurred, where most Ethiopians, perhaps finding trade too pedestrian, began to look down upon merchants, preferring to idealize the country's revered warriors and spiritual leaders [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Into this void stepped Greek, [Armenian](/Armenians), and Arab traders, who established footholds and effectively became the economic intermediaries between Ethiopia and the external world [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). These Arab traders eventually permeated the interior, gradually monopolizing virtually all commercial activity, save for the most rudimentary petty trade [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

When the Italian occupation of Ethiopia finally concluded in 1941, it left behind an economic structure that, for all intents and purposes, largely resembled what it had been for centuries [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). While the Italians did leave a few modest improvements—notably in [communications](/Communication), particularly road construction, and some nascent attempts at establishing small industries and introducing [commercial farming](/Commercial_farming), especially in Eritrea, which they had occupied since 1890—these changes were, to put it mildly, limited [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). The reality was that only a minute fraction of the population participated in the monetized economy. Trade was predominantly conducted through [barter](/Barter), [wage labor](/Wage_labour) was scarce, economic units were largely self-sufficient, [foreign trade](/Foreign_trade) was negligible, and the domestic market for manufactured goods remained astonishingly small [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

The late 1940s and 1950s saw little deviation from this static economic picture [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). The government, with its peculiar priorities, channeled its development efforts primarily into expanding the [bureaucratic](/Bureaucracy) apparatus and its associated ancillary services [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). The vast majority of farmers continued to cultivate small plots or herd livestock, employing traditional and often primitive methods that barely afforded them a [subsistence standard of living](/Subsistence_economy) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). In the drier regions, many [nomadic peoples](/Nomad) continued their seasonal migrations, tending to their livestock [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). While the agricultural sector did experience some marginal growth, the [industrial sector](/Industrial_sector_in_Ethiopia) remained a rather insignificant footnote in the overall economic narrative [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

By the early 1950s, [Emperor Haile Selassie I](/Haile_Selassie) (whose reign spanned from 1930 to 1974) began to vocalize renewed aspirations for a fundamental shift from a subsistence-based economy to a more robust agro-industrial one [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Achieving this ambitious transformation, he recognized, would necessitate substantial investments in infrastructure to unlock resources, a solid material base to genuinely improve living conditions, and significant enhancements in health, education, communications, and other essential services [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). A cornerstone of the emperor's new economic policy was the implementation of centrally managed [development plans](/Urban_planning) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

The First Five-Year Plan (1957–1961) was designed to foster the development of a strong infrastructure, with a particular emphasis on transportation, construction, and communications, aiming to bridge the geographical and economic divides between isolated regions [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Following this, the Second Five-Year Plan (1962–1967) marked the commencement of a more ambitious 20-year program, explicitly intended to transform Ethiopia's predominantly agricultural economy into a more diversified agro-industrial one [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). The Third Five-Year Plan (1968–1973) continued this trajectory, seeking to bolster Ethiopia's economic well-being by elevating [manufacturing](/Manufacturing) and agro-industrial performance [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Crucially, and in a departure from its predecessors, the third plan also articulated the government's newfound willingness to expand educational opportunities and to genuinely improve the lot of peasant agriculture [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

During the First Five-Year Plan, the [gross national product](/Gross_national_product) (GNP) managed a 3.2 percent annual growth rate, falling short of the rather optimistic projected figure of 3.7 percent. Furthermore, growth targets in critical economic sectors such as agriculture, manufacturing, and mining remained unmet [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). The Planning Commission, with a certain lack of accountability, never formally evaluated the performance of the Second and Third Five-Year Plans, largely, one might cynically assume, due to a chronic shortage of qualified personnel [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Nevertheless, according to data from the Ethiopian government's Central Statistical Authority, the period between 1960/61 and 1973/74 did witness sustained [economic growth](/Economic_growth) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Specifically, from 1960 to 1970, Ethiopia enjoyed an average annual 4.4 percent growth rate in [per capita](/Per_capita) [gross domestic product (GDP)](/Gross_domestic_product) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Relative to its regional counterparts, Ethiopia's economic performance during this era was, charitably speaking, mixed [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

By the early 1970s, Ethiopia's economy had not only begun to expand but also showed nascent signs of diversification into areas like manufacturing and services [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Yet, these developments, for all their promise, largely failed to translate into tangible improvements in the daily lives of the majority of Ethiopians [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Approximately four-fifths of the population remained subsistence farmers, locked in a cycle of poverty, their meager production largely consumed by taxes, rents, debt payments, and, inevitably, bribes [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

The [1974 revolution](/Ethiopian_Civil_War) proved to be a watershed moment, leading to the dramatic [nationalization](/Nationalization) and wholesale restructuring of the Ethiopian economy [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Following this upheaval, the country's economic trajectory can be broadly delineated into four distinct phases [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). The initial period, from 1974 to 1978, was characterized by intense internal political turmoil, widespread armed conflict, and radical [institutional reform](/Institutional_reform) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Economic growth during this time was virtually nonexistent; instead, the government's sweeping nationalization measures and the highly unstable [political climate](/Political_climate) precipitated significant economic dislocation across various sectors, particularly agriculture and manufacturing [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Consequently, GDP during this tumultuous phase increased at a dismal average annual rate of only 0.4 percent [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

In the second phase (1978–1980), the economy, with a surprising resilience, began to demonstrate signs of recovery as the government gradually consolidated its power and more effectively implemented its institutional reforms [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). More critically, security conditions improved markedly as both internal and external threats began to recede [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). During this brief reprieve, GDP grew at a more respectable average annual rate of 5.7 percent [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

However, the third phase (1980–1985) saw the economy endure a significant setback [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). With the exception of Ethiopian [fiscal year](/Fiscal_year) (EFY) 1982/83, GDP growth experienced a disheartening decline [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). Manufacturing also took a downturn, and the agricultural sector plunged into a full-blown crisis, exacerbated by a severe drought that inevitably led to widespread and devastating [famine](/Famine) [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

The fourth period (1985–1990) offered little relief, with the economy continuing its pattern of stagnation [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41). While GDP and the manufacturing sector did register some growth during these years, with GDP increasing at an average annual rate of 5 percent, these modest achievements were largely overshadowed and ultimately undercut by the lingering, destructive effects of the 1984-85 drought, which contributed significantly to the economy's overall stagnation [41](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-41).

Since 1991, the Ethiopian government has, with a renewed sense of purpose, embarked on a comprehensive program of economic reform. This has included the [privatization](/Privatization) of state enterprises and a much-needed rationalization of [government regulation](/Government_regulation) [42](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Seid_et_al._2016-42). While this process is, as these things often are, still very much ongoing, these reforms have demonstrably succeeded in attracting crucial [foreign direct investment](/Foreign_direct_investment) into the country.

In 2015, Ethiopia was home to 2,700 millionaires, a number that had more than doubled since 2007. Their wealth, it's noted, was primarily accumulated through the exploitation of specific [economic rents](/Economic_rent)—think banks, mines, and similar ventures—rather than through substantial investment in structural and strategic sectors like industrial production or infrastructure [43](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Piot_2017-43). This pattern, some suggest, is unlikely to genuinely foster broad economic development or pose any significant competitive threat to established Western multinationals.

The Ethiopian government has also been diligently intensifying its efforts to draw in foreign investors, with a particular focus on the [textile sector](/Textile_industry). These investors are now afforded rather generous incentives: they can import their machinery without incurring customs duties, enjoy a [tax exemption](/Tax_exemption) for a full decade, benefit from rents significantly below market rates, and access exceptionally inexpensive water and electricity [44](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-G%C3%A9rand_2019-44). Consequently, major international brands such as Decathlon, H&M, and Huajian have established operations in the country. These companies, of course, also benefit from a remarkably cheap labor force, with monthly salaries hovering around a meager 35 euros. Adding to the appeal, existing trade agreements between Ethiopia and the European Union permit these companies to export their goods duty-free [44](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-G%C3%A9rand_2019-44). It’s almost too good to be true, for some.

