## Sectors

### Agriculture, forestry and fishing

Coffee sorting process is huge since Ethiopia exports over a billion dollars' worth of coffee globally
Map of economic activities in Ethiopia and Eritrea (1976)

•
See also: [Agriculture in Ethiopia](/Agriculture_in_Ethiopia), [Fishing in Ethiopia](/Fishing_in_Ethiopia), and [Forestry in Ethiopia](/Forestry_in_Ethiopia)

As of the latest available data in 2023, [agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Ethiopia) continues to be the undisputed backbone of the Ethiopian economy. It accounts for nearly 36% of the country's [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product), generates a staggering 81% of its total exports, and, perhaps most critically, employs a vast 73% of the entire [labour force](/Workforce) [45](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-CIA_Factbook_Ethiopia-45). The influence of agriculture extends far beyond direct production, underpinning numerous other economic activities, including the marketing, processing, and export of its diverse agricultural bounty. Production within this sector is overwhelmingly subsistence-oriented, meaning most farmers grow just enough to feed themselves and their families. Nevertheless, a substantial portion of commodity exports originates from a smaller, but vital, agricultural [cash-crop](/Cash_crop) sector.

The principal crops cultivated across Ethiopia are varied and essential: [coffee](/Coffee_production_in_Ethiopia) (a perennial star), [pulses](/Pulse_(legume)) (such as various types of beans), [oilseeds](/Rapeseed), [cereals](/Cereal), potatoes, [sugarcane](/Sugarcane), and an array of vegetables. Exports are almost exclusively agricultural commodities, with [coffee](/Coffee) maintaining its historic role as the largest earner of foreign exchange. However, a new contender has emerged: the burgeoning flower industry, which has become a significant source of revenue. For the 2005/2006 fiscal year (the most recent available detailed data), Ethiopia's coffee exports constituted 0.9% of global exports, while both [oilseeds](/Oilseeds) and flowers each contributed 0.5% [46](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-IMF_Country_Report_08/259-46). Ethiopia also holds the distinction of being Africa's second-largest producer of [maize](/Maize) [47](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Economist_food_chain-47). In 2000, the country's extensive [livestock](/Livestock) sector contributed a substantial 19% to the total [GDP](/Gross_domestic_product) [48](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-FAO_Livestock_Sector_Brief-48).

As of 2008, a rather unsettling trend began to emerge: certain countries, heavily reliant on food imports (such as [Saudi Arabia](/Saudi_Arabia)), started to strategize the acquisition and [development](/Land_development) of vast tracts of arable land in developing nations, with Ethiopia being a prime target [49](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Blas_2008-49). This phenomenon, often referred to as "[land grabbing](/Land_grabbing)," has understandably ignited fears that food produced on these lands might be predominantly exported to more prosperous nations, potentially exacerbating food shortages among the local population [49](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Blas_2008-49). A classic case of globalized priorities clashing with local needs, if you ask me.

[Forest products](/Forest_product) in Ethiopia are primarily sourced as logs, which are then predominantly utilized in various construction projects. Beyond this, the broader range of [silvicultural](/Silviculture) products finds applications in both [construction](/Construction) and [manufacturing](/Manufacturing), and critically, serve as essential [energy sources](/Energy_development) for a large segment of the population [50](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Wakjira_2007-50) [51](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Lemenih_2011-51).

Given its landlocked status, Ethiopia's [fisheries](/Fishery) are entirely confined to [fresh water](/Fresh_water) environments, lacking any marine [coastline](/Coast) for oceanic harvests. Despite a continuous increase in total production since 2007, the fishing industry remains a rather minuscule component of the overall economy. Fishing activities are overwhelmingly [artisanal](/Artisanal_fishing), relying on traditional methods. In 2014, approximately 45,000 fishermen were engaged in this sector, though a mere 30% of them were employed on a full-time basis [52](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-FAO_Fisheries_Country_Profile-52).

In 2018, Ethiopia's agricultural output included a diverse range of commodities [53](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-FAO_production_2018-53):

