### Textile industry

It's a rather stark reality that employees in Ethiopian [garment factories](/Textile_manufacturing), who diligently produce for globally recognized brands such as [Guess](/Guess), [H&M](/H%26M), or [Calvin Klein](/Calvin_Klein), receive a monthly salary that barely registers at 26 dollars [54](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Le_Monde_H&M-54). These exceptionally low wages, as one might predictably surmise, have unfortunately led to a cascade of issues: diminished [productivity](/Productivity), frequent labor strikes, and an alarmingly high employee turnover rate. A 2019 report from the Stern Centre for Business and Human Rights at [New York University](/New_York_University) revealed that some factories, in a rather telling indictment of the system, have found themselves replacing their entire workforce, on average, every 12 months [54](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Le_Monde_H&M-54). A truly sustainable model, I'm sure.

### Minerals and mining

•
This section is an excerpt from [Mining in Ethiopia](/Mining_in_Ethiopia).[edit]

[Microcline](/Microcline) from the [Kenticha mine](/Kenticha_mine), [Oromia Region](/Oromia_Region), Ethiopia.

[Mining](/Mining_in_Ethiopia) plays a role of increasing importance in the [economy of Ethiopia](/Economy_of_Ethiopia), serving as a crucial strategy for diversification away from the traditional dominance of [agriculture](/Agriculture_in_Ethiopia). Presently, however, the mining sector contributes a mere 1% to the national [GDP](/GDP), indicating significant untapped potential. Key commodities driving the country's export-oriented growth strategy within this sector include [gold](/Gold_mining), valuable [gemstones](/Gemstone) (such as diamonds and sapphires), and various industrial minerals [55](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Guardian_Gold-55).

Ethiopia is known to possess deposits of [coal](/Coal), [opal](/Opal), a range of [gemstones](/Gemstones), [kaolin](/Kaolin), iron ore, [soda ash](/Soda_ash), and [tantalum](/Tantalum). Yet, among these, only [gold](/Gold) is extracted in truly significant quantities. The extraction of [salt](/Salt) from the expansive salt beds within the [Afar Depression](/Afar_Depression), as well as from salt springs located in the southern [Dire](/Dire_(woreda)) and [Afder](/Afder_(woreda)) districts, is primarily for internal consumption, with only a negligible amount destined for export markets.

[Tantalum](/Tantalum) mining has also proven to be a profitable venture [56](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Belda_2006-56). It was noted in the late 1980s that the mineral industry's contribution was rather marginal, accounting for less than 0.2 percent of Ethiopia's [GDP](/GDP) [57](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Ofcansky_2004-57). However, the landscape has shifted, with gold mining now recognized as a pivotal development sector for the country. Gold export revenues, which were a modest US$5 million in 2001, witnessed a dramatic surge, reaching US$602 million by 2012 [58](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-UK_Trade_and_Investment-58). In 2001 alone, gold production amounted to approximately 3.4 tons [59](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Library_of_Congress_Ethiopia_country_profile_2-59). Clearly, some things are more valuable than others.

### Energy

•
Main article: [Energy in Ethiopia](/Energy_in_Ethiopia)

[Waterpower](/Hydropower) and the country's extensive forests stand as Ethiopia's primary indigenous energy sources. The nation relies heavily on hydropower, deriving approximately 90 percent of its electricity needs from this renewable source [60](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Library_of_Congress_Ethiopia_country_profile_3-60). This reliance, however, means that [electricity generation](/Electricity_generation), much like agriculture, is precariously dependent on abundant rainfall – a fact that introduces a certain vulnerability to the energy supply. The current installed capacity for electricity generation is rated at roughly 2000 megawatts, with ambitious plans for expansion to a formidable 10,000 megawatts. Generally, the majority of Ethiopians depend on forests for nearly all their energy requirements, primarily for cooking and heating, as well as for construction materials. This heavy dependence has, unfortunately, resulted in the extensive [deforestation](/Ethiopian_deforestation) of much of the highlands over the past three decades [60](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Library_of_Congress_Ethiopia_country_profile_3-60). A truly sustainable model, I'm sure. Ethiopia has, with a grand gesture, laid out plans to invest an estimated $40 billion in 71 distinct energy projects by the year 2030 [61](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Clean_Energy_Projects-61).

Ethiopian Prime Minister [Ahmed](/Abiy_Ahmed) with Indian counterpart Prime Minister [Narendra Modi](/Narendra_Modi) meeting for Ethiopia's admission to the alliance

Less than half of Ethiopia's towns and cities are currently integrated into the national electricity grid, highlighting a significant disparity in energy access. The country's petroleum requirements are entirely met through imports of refined products, although some oil is reportedly transported overland from Sudan. The search for oil within Ethiopia itself has been a protracted endeavor, ongoing for decades, ever since [Emperor Haile Selassie I](/Haile_Selassie_of_Ethiopia) granted a 50-year concession to [SOCONY-Vacuum](/SOCONY-Vacuum) in September 1945 [62](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Time_Sinco_Places_a_Bet-62).

Recent discoveries of significant oil and gas reserves across [East Africa](/East_Africa) have thrust the region into the spotlight as a new, albeit nascent, player in the global oil and gas industry. While the sheer scale of the massive gas fields in East Africa is undeniably exciting, the pronounced decline in global oil prices and the prevailing expectations for a prolonged period of low prices (an "L-shaped recovery," as the optimists call it) are increasingly challenging the economic viability of developing this industry in the region [63](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Mineweb_East_Africa_gas-63) [64](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Riscura_Bright_Africa-64). Ethiopia's own gas reserves are estimated at a substantial 4 [trillion cubic feet](/1000000000_(number)) (110×10^9 m^3), with ongoing exploration for both gas and oil actively underway in the [Gambela Region](/Gambela_Region), which borders [South Sudan](/South_Sudan) [60](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Library_of_Congress_Ethiopia_country_profile_3-60).

These discoveries were initially projected to catalyze billions of dollars in annual investment into the region over the coming decade [65](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-IBT_Oil_And_Gas_Discoveries-65). According to estimates from BMI, the findings in recent years in East Africa surpass those of any other region globally, with further discoveries anticipated in the near future. However, as noted, the persistent fall in global oil prices casts a long shadow, threatening the commercial viability of many of these promising gas prospects [66](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-NYT_Oil_Prices-66). It seems even geology can't escape the fickle whims of the market.

### Manufacturing

•
Main article: [Manufacturing in Ethiopia](/Manufacturing_in_Ethiopia)

A concerted program to [privatize](/Privatization) state-owned enterprises has been in motion since the late 1990s, signaling a gradual shift away from centralized control [60](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Library_of_Congress_Ethiopia_country_profile_3-60). Over the past years, Ethiopia has witnessed a significant surge in its [manufacturing](/Manufacturing_in_Ethiopia) sector. This growth has been particularly evident in the establishment of several industrial parks, many of which are strategically focused on the [textile industry](/Textile_industry), aiming to leverage the country's competitive advantages in this area.

### Transport

•
Main article: [Transport in Ethiopia](/Transport_in_Ethiopia)

Prior to the outbreak of the [Eritrean–Ethiopian War](/Eritrean%E2%80%93Ethiopian_War) (1998–2000), landlocked Ethiopia was almost entirely reliant on the Eritrean seaports of [Asseb](/Asseb) and [Massawa](/Massawa) for its international trade. This dependence, predictably, became a critical vulnerability once hostilities commenced.

[Ethiopian Airlines](/Ethiopian_Airlines) is the largest airline in Africa, and one of the highest grossing airlines in the world with a revenue over 5 billion USD.

The largest bank in Ethiopia, the commercial bank's former headquarters in Addis Ababa, now serving as one of the other head offices.

As of 2005, Ethiopia primarily utilizes the ports of [Djibouti](/Djibouti), which are efficiently connected to the capital, [Addis Ababa](/Addis_Ababa), by the [Addis Ababa – Djibouti Railway](/Rail_transport_in_Ethiopia). To a lesser extent, the port of [Port Sudan](/Port_Sudan) in [Sudan](/Sudan) also serves as an alternative trade gateway. In May 2005, the Ethiopian government initiated negotiations to explore the possibility of using the port of [Berbera](/Berbera) in [Somaliland](/Somaliland), further diversifying its access to the sea. The government, with its usual ambitious projections, anticipates a staggering $74 billion investment in the transportation sector by 2030 [67](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-ITA_Ethiopia_Transport-67).

#### Road

As of 2016, Ethiopia boasts an extensive network of 113,066 kilometres (70,256 mi) of all-weather roads [68](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-export.gov_Ethiopia_Roads-68). This represents a significant investment in connecting its vast and diverse regions.

#### Air

[Ethiopian Airlines](/Ethiopian_Airlines) stands as Africa's largest and most consistently profitable airline, a remarkable achievement in a competitive global industry [69](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-CAPA_Ethiopian_Airlines_2015-69). The airline proudly serves 132 destinations across the globe, operating a modern fleet of 141 aircraft.

#### Rail

The Ethiopian railway network has been undergoing a period of rapid and significant expansion. In 2015, [Addis Ababa](/Addis_Ababa) celebrated the opening of Africa's first light rail system, a landmark achievement in urban transport. Following this, in 2017, the electric [Addis Ababa-Djibouti](/Addis_Ababa%E2%80%93Djibouti_Railway) railway commenced operations, providing a vital, modern link to the sea. Currently, two additional electric railways are actively under construction: the [Awash-Woldiya](/Awash%E2%80%93Weldiya_Railway) line and the [Woldiya-Mekelle](/Weldiya%E2%80%93Mekelle_Railway) line, further extending the country's rail infrastructure.

### Telecommunications and technology

•
See also: [Telecommunications in Ethiopia](/Telecommunications_in_Ethiopia), [Media in Ethiopia](/Media_in_Ethiopia), and [Internet in Ethiopia](/Internet_in_Ethiopia)

Historically, [telecommunications](/Telecommunications_in_Ethiopia) services in Ethiopia were the exclusive domain of a state-owned monopoly, Ethio Telecom, formerly known as the [Ethiopian Telecommunications Corporation](/Ethiopian_Telecommunications_Corporation). However, a significant shift occurred in October 2022, when [Safaricom Telecommunications Ethiopia](/Safaricom_Telecommunications_Ethiopia) officially launched its services, marking its entry as the country's inaugural private operator [70](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Reuters_Safaricom-70). This move signals a new era of competition and potential innovation in the sector.

Ethiopian shipment cargo ship, docked in Djibouti

In 2020, government ministers unveiled a comprehensive national transformation strategy aptly named "Digital Ethiopia 2025" [71](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Blavatnik_Digital_Roadmap-71) [72](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Addis_Insight_Digital_Strategy-72). The overarching aim of this ambitious initiative is to systematically prepare the country for the profound shifts and opportunities presented by the development of an economy fundamentally based on digital technology. It's an acknowledgment that the future, like it or not, is digital.

### Tourism

•
Main article: [Tourism in Ethiopia](/Tourism_in_Ethiopia)

The [services sector](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy) in Ethiopia, for all its grand pronouncements, consists almost entirely of [tourism](/Tourism_in_Ethiopia), with some additional economic activity stemming from wholesale and retail trade, transportation, and communications. Developed with a certain zeal in the 1960s, the tourism industry suffered a precipitous decline during the tumultuous late 1970s and 1980s under the military government. Recovery, a slow and arduous process, began only in the 1990s. However, its growth has been consistently hampered by a lack of adequate infrastructure, particularly suitable hotels, the persistent impact of droughts, the disruptive [1998–2000 war with Eritrea](/Eritrean%E2%80%93Ethiopian_War), and the ever-present specter of terrorism.

In 2002, a little over 156,000 tourists graced the country with their presence, many of whom were Ethiopians visiting from abroad, collectively spending more than US$77 million [60](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Library_of_Congress_Ethiopia_country_profile_3-60). By 2008, the number of inbound tourists had increased to a more robust 330,000 [73](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-UNdata_Ethiopia-73). A decade later, in 2019, Ethiopia proudly registered a record 812,000 tourist arrivals, generating a revenue of $3.55 billion, which accounted for 4.2 percent of the gross national product [74](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_data_tourism-74) [75](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Project-E_Tourism-75). In a moment that probably surprised many, in 2015, Ethiopia was rather unexpectedly crowned the "World's Best Tourist Destination" by the European Council on Tourism and Trade [76](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-CNN_World's_Best_Tourist_Destination-76). One can only imagine the criteria.

