Ethiopia's economy experienced a period of remarkably strong and broad-based growth, averaging an impressive 9.4% annually from the 2010/11 to 2019/20 fiscal years. However, this robust momentum saw a deceleration, with real [gross domestic product](/Gross_domestic_product) (GDP) growth slowing to 6.1% in 2019/20, a direct consequence of the global [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic) [81](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Overview-81). The lion's share of this growth was attributed to the [industry sector](/Secondary_sector_of_the_economy), particularly construction, and the burgeoning [services sector](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy). Interestingly, the [agricultural sector](/Primary_sector_of_the_economy) remained largely unaffected by the pandemic's immediate economic fallout, and its contribution to overall growth actually saw a slight improvement in 2019/20 compared to the preceding year. On the demand side, growth was primarily driven by private consumption and, increasingly, by public investment, the latter assuming an ever more critical role in sustaining economic expansion [81](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Overview-81).

