## Poverty

•
•
This section is an excerpt from [Poverty in Ethiopia](/Poverty_in_Ethiopia).[edit]

Share of population in extreme poverty over time

The [African country](/Africa) of [Ethiopia](/Ethiopia) has, for better or worse, made what some might call "strides" in its efforts to alleviate [poverty](/Poverty) since the year 2000. At that time, its poverty rate was, rather unflatteringly, assessed as one of the highest among all nations [82](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Poverty_Assessment-82). The country has indeed achieved notable progress in several areas pertaining to the [Millennium Development Goals](/Millennium_Development_Goals), including a reduction in various diseases and a decrease in the rate of child mortality [82](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Poverty_Assessment-82). Despite these improvements, a candid assessment reveals that poverty remains alarmingly high within the nation [82](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Poverty_Assessment-82). Based on the most recent data from 2019, a staggering 68.7% of the population is still impacted by [multidimensional poverty](/Multidimensional_Poverty_Index), with an additional 18.4% precariously vulnerable to it [83](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-UNDP_MPI_2023-83). It seems "strides" can still leave you miles from the finish line.

One of the primary factors credited with driving down poverty figures was the strategic expansion of the agricultural sector [82](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Poverty_Assessment-82). This enabled poor farmers to command higher [food prices](/Food_prices) for their produce, theoretically boosting their sales and revenue. However, this expansion came with an unfortunate, almost inevitable, side effect: a disproportionate cost borne by the country's poorest citizens, who found themselves unable to afford the now-higher-priced food [82](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Poverty_Assessment-82). A truly effective solution, it seems, often creates new problems. One of the most significant challenges in genuinely alleviating this pervasive issue lies in fundamentally restructuring Ethiopia's economy, transitioning it from its deeply entrenched agricultural base to a more diversified, industry-based model [82](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-World_Bank_Poverty_Assessment-82). The current strategy for tackling poverty in Ethiopia involves a pragmatic approach: building upon existing government systems and leveraging development programs that are already operational within the country [84](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-UNICEF_Annual_Report_2017-84). A cautious approach, perhaps, but one that avoids reinventing the wheel, however rusty it might be.

