## External trade

Ethiopian exports in 2006

Until 2013, the primary agricultural export crop, and thus a major source of foreign exchange, was [coffee](/Coffee_production_in_Ethiopia), accounting for approximately 26.4% of Ethiopia's total foreign exchange earnings. However, in a significant shift that began in early 2014, [oilseeds](/Oilseeds) exports emerged as an even more dominant contributor to the nation's trade balance [85](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Ethiosports_Oilseed-85). Despite this shift, [coffee](/Coffee) remains absolutely critical to the Ethiopian economy; over 15 million people, representing a quarter of the entire population, directly derive their livelihoods from the coffee sector [86](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-African_Business_Ethiopian_coffee-86).

Other notable exports include live animals, various [leather](/Leather) and leather products, chemicals, [gold](/Gold), [pulses](/Legume), oilseeds, fresh flowers, fruits, vegetables, and [khat](/Khat) (also known as qat), a leafy [shrub](/Shrub) possessing distinct [psychotropic](/Psychoactive_drug) qualities when chewed. A rather eclectic mix, wouldn't you say? Cross-border trade, particularly among [pastoralists](/Pastoralism), is frequently informal, operating largely beyond the direct oversight and regulatory mechanisms of the state. In [East Africa](/East_Africa), a staggering 95% of cross-border trade occurs through unofficial channels. This includes the unofficial trade of live cattle, camels, sheep, and goats from Ethiopia, which are then sold into neighboring [Somalia](/Somalia), [Kenya](/Kenya), and [Djibouti](/Djibouti). This illicit trade generates an estimated total value of between US$250 million and US$300 million annually, a figure that dwarfs the official statistics by a factor of 100 [87](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Pavanello_2010-87).

This informal trade, while unregulated, actually contributes to lowering [food prices](/Food_prices), enhancing food security, easing border tensions, and fostering a degree of [regional integration](/Regional_integration) [87](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Pavanello_2010-87). However, it's not without its drawbacks; the unregulated and undocumented nature of this commerce carries inherent risks, such as facilitating the easier spread of diseases across the region. Furthermore, the Ethiopian government is reportedly rather displeased by the substantial loss of potential [tax revenue](/Tax_revenue) and valuable foreign exchange earnings that bypass official channels [87](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Pavanello_2010-87). Recent initiatives have been launched, with varying degrees of success, to document and regulate this trade, aiming to bring it into the formal economy.

Dependent on a handful of vulnerable crops for its crucial foreign exchange earnings and heavily reliant on imported oil, Ethiopia frequently faces a deficit in its foreign exchange reserves. The government, characterized by its financially conservative stance, has implemented measures to address this persistent issue, including stringent [import controls](/Import_controls) and sharply reduced [subsidies](/Subsidy) on retail gasoline prices. Nevertheless, the largely subsistence-based economy struggles to support high military expenditures, provide adequate drought relief, fund ambitious development plans, and cover indispensable imports like oil. Consequently, it remains significantly dependent on [foreign assistance](/Foreign_aid_to_Ethiopia).

In December 1999, Ethiopia signed a substantial $1.4 [billion](/1000000000_(number)) joint venture agreement with the Malaysian oil company, [Petronas](/Petronas), with the aim of developing a vast [natural gas field](/Natural_gas_field) situated in the [Somali Region](/Somali_Region). By 2010, however, the implementation of this ambitious project had failed to progress as anticipated, leading to Petronas losing its license to develop the field [88](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-New_Business_Ethiopia_oil-88) [89](/Economy_of_Ethiopia#cite_note-Upstream_Online_Petronas-89). The field is now under the investment purview of the Chinese company, Poly-GCL Petroleum.

Ethiopia has already begun exporting electricity to neighboring countries such as Kenya, South Sudan, and Djibouti, a venture that reportedly generates US$300 million annually. Following the completion of the monumental [Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam (GERD)](/Grand_Ethiopian_Renaissance_Dam) in 2023, the total revenue projected from electricity exports to neighboring countries is expected to surge to an impressive US$1 billion annually [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed). This dam, now fully operational, stands as not only the largest hydroelectric power plant in Africa but also ranks among the 20 largest globally [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed). A testament to ambitious infrastructure, or a symbol of regional tension, depending on your perspective.

